8. What is the difference between switchMap, mergeMap, concatMap, exhaustMap?
| Operator    | Behavior                                                                                     |                                   |
|-------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------| 
| switchMap   | Cancels previous inner observable when a new value is emitted. Only the latest inner observable is active. | 
              | Use Case:  Search autocomplete, where you want to cancel previous requests. |
Example:
search$.pipe(debounceTime(300),
  switchMap(term => this.http.get(`/search?q=${term}`)))
  
| mergeMap    | Merges all inner observables concurrently. All emitted values are included in the output. 
              | Use Case:  Handling multiple concurrent requests, like loading multiple resources at once. |
| concatMap   | Queues inner observables and processes them one at a time. Each inner observable is completed before the next one starts.|
              | Use Case:  When order matters, like saving a series of form submissions. |
| exhaustMap  | Ignores new values while the current inner observable is still active. 
                Only the first inner observable is processed until it completes. 
              | Use Case:  Handling login requests, where you want to ignore additional clicks until the first request completes. |  
| flatMap     | Alias for mergeMap. Merges all inner observables concurrently. All emitted values are included in the output. 
              | flatMap is just an alias of mergeMap. There is no behavioral difference. In modern RxJS, mergeMap is preferred.
              | Use Case:  Same as mergeMap, but with a more intuitive name for flat mapping operations. |
